---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";
import { saudiCostOfLiving } from "../../data/saudi/cost-of-living";
import { buildBreadcrumbs, buildArticleSchema, buildFAQSchema } from "../../lib/seo";
import RelatedLinks from "../../components/ui/RelatedLinks.astro";
import SourcesBlock from "../../components/ui/SourcesBlock.astro";
import FAQAccordion from "../../components/ui/FAQAccordion.astro";
import CostOfLivingSimulator from "../../components/calculators/CostOfLivingSimulator";

const faqs = [
  { question: "How much does a single expat need to live in Saudi Arabia in 2026?", answer: "A single expat needs SAR 4,500-8,000 (~EUR 1,080-1,920) per month depending on city and lifestyle. This covers a one-bedroom apartment (SAR 2,000-4,500), groceries (SAR 700-1,200), transport (SAR 400-700), utilities (SAR 200-400), and personal expenses. Riyadh is slightly more expensive than Jeddah, and both are more expensive than the Eastern Province." },
  { question: "Is Saudi Arabia cheaper than Dubai for expats?", answer: "Yes, substantially. Riyadh is 25-40% cheaper than Dubai for comparable lifestyles. Housing is the biggest difference: a one-bedroom in Riyadh costs SAR 2,500-5,000 (~EUR 600-1,200) vs AED 6,000-10,000 (~EUR 1,500-2,500) in Dubai. However, Saudi Arabia charges 15% VAT vs the UAE's 5%, which partially offsets the savings on non-housing expenses." },
  { question: "What is VAT in Saudi Arabia and how does it affect costs?", answer: "Saudi Arabia charges 15% VAT on most goods and services, the highest rate in the GCC. This was increased from 5% in July 2020. Some essentials including basic food items, healthcare, and education may have exemptions or zero-rating. The VAT is included in the displayed price at most retail outlets. For a household spending SAR 5,000/month on taxable goods, the VAT component is SAR 750." },
  { question: "How much do families spend on schools in Saudi Arabia?", answer: "International school fees in Saudi Arabia range from SAR 10,000 to SAR 80,000 (~EUR 2,400-19,200) per year. Indian-curriculum schools are cheapest at SAR 10,000-22,000. British and American schools charge SAR 25,000-60,000. Premium institutions in Riyadh and Jeddah reach SAR 60,000-80,000. Many employers include education allowances covering one to three children." },
  { question: "What is the savings rate for expats in Saudi Arabia?", answer: "Saudi Arabia offers the highest savings rate among Gulf countries. Single professionals commonly save 35-50% of gross income. Families with employer-provided housing can save 40-60%. The key factors are zero income tax, low base costs for housing and transport, and employer benefits that offset major expenses like housing and education." },
];

const breadcrumbs = [{ name: "Home", url: "https://arabiaexpat.com/" }, { name: "Saudi Arabia", url: "https://arabiaexpat.com/saudi-arabia/guide/" }, { name: "Cost of Living", url: "https://arabiaexpat.com/saudi-arabia/cost-of-living/" }];
---
<GuideLayout title="Saudi Cost of Living 2026: Rent, Food & 15% VAT Impact" description="Monthly budget Saudi Arabia: SAR 4,500-8,000 single, SAR 12,000-22,000 family. 30% cheaper than Dubai despite 15% VAT. Riyadh, Jeddah and Khobar data." canonical="/saudi-arabia/cost-of-living/" schemas={[buildBreadcrumbs(breadcrumbs), buildArticleSchema("Saudi Arabia Cost of Living 2026: Rent, Food and Prices", "Detailed Saudi cost of living guide for 2026.", "https://arabiaexpat.com/saudi-arabia/cost-of-living/", "2025-01-15", "2026-06-01"), buildFAQSchema(faqs)]} breadcrumbs={[{ name: "Home", url: "/" }, { name: "Saudi Arabia", url: "/saudi-arabia/guide/" }, { name: "Cost of Living", url: "/saudi-arabia/cost-of-living/" }]}>

<div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 rounded-xl">
  <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3">Saudi Arabia Savings Rate Calculator</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">Enter your salary and city to see your potential savings rate in Saudi Arabia.</p>
  <form id="saSavings" class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
    <div>
      <label class="block text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-1" for="saSalary">Monthly salary (SAR)</label>
      <input type="number" id="saSalary" value="15000" min="1000" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 px-3 py-2 text-sm" />
    </div>
    <div>
      <label class="block text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-1" for="saCity">City</label>
      <select id="saCity" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 px-3 py-2 text-sm">
        <option value="riyadh" selected>Riyadh</option>
        <option value="jeddah">Jeddah</option>
        <option value="dammam">Dammam/Khobar</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div>
      <label class="block text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-1" for="saHouse">Housing provided?</label>
      <select id="saHouse" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 px-3 py-2 text-sm">
        <option value="no" selected>No, I pay rent</option>
        <option value="yes">Yes, employer provides</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div class="sm:col-span-3">
      <button type="button" onclick="_calcCostOfLiving()" class="w-full sm:w-auto px-5 py-2.5 bg-teal-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-teal-700 transition-colors">Calculate Savings</button>
    </div>
    <div id="saResult" class="sm:col-span-3 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 min-h-[2rem]"></div>
  </form>
</div>

<h1>Saudi Arabia Cost of Living 2026</h1>

<div class="not-prose mb-8">
<CostOfLivingSimulator client:visible defaultCity="riyadh" />
</div>

<p>Saudi Arabia offers the highest savings potential of any major Gulf destination, and understanding exactly where your money goes each month is the key to unlocking that potential. Despite charging the highest VAT rate in the GCC at 15%, the kingdom's dramatically lower base prices for housing, transportation, food, and utilities more than compensate. A one-bedroom apartment in central Riyadh costs SAR 2,500 to SAR 5,000 per month, roughly 40% to 60% less than comparable accommodation in Dubai. Petrol at SAR 2.18 per liter is less than half the price in Europe. Electricity through the Saudi Electricity Company benefits from government subsidies that keep residential rates among the lowest in the world. These structural cost advantages, combined with zero personal income tax, create a financial environment where disciplined expatriates routinely save 35% to 50% of their gross income, and those with employer-provided housing can push savings rates above 60%.</p>

<p>The key to accurate budgeting in Saudi Arabia is understanding that costs vary meaningfully across the kingdom's three main expatriate cities. <a href="/saudi-arabia/riyadh/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Riyadh</a>, the capital and largest city, is the most expensive, driven by Vision 2030 demand pushing up rents in premium northern neighborhoods. <a href="/saudi-arabia/jeddah/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Jeddah</a>, the Red Sea port city, sits 10% to 15% below Riyadh in most categories. <a href="/saudi-arabia/dammam/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">The Eastern Province</a> (Dammam, Khobar, Dhahran) offers the lowest costs, particularly for expatriates with Aramco or energy sector employers who provide subsidized compound housing. This guide breaks down costs across all three regions with 2026 pricing data, helping you build an accurate monthly budget before accepting a job offer or arriving in the kingdom.</p>

{saudiCostOfLiving.cities.map((city) => (
<>
<h2>{city.name} Cost Breakdown</h2>
<h3>Housing</h3>
<div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto mb-4">
<table class="w-full text-sm"><thead><tr class="bg-teal-600 text-white"><th class="px-3 py-2 text-left rounded-tl-lg">Type</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">Min (SAR)</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">Max (SAR)</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">EUR Equiv.</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right rounded-tr-lg">USD Equiv.</th></tr></thead>
<tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">Studio</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.studioApartment.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.studioApartment.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.min / 3.75).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.max / 3.75).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">1 Bedroom</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.oneBedroom.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.oneBedroom.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.min / 3.75).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.max / 3.75).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">2 Bedroom</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.twoBedroom.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.twoBedroom.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.min / 3.75).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.max / 3.75).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">Family Villa</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.familyVilla.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.familyVilla.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.min / 3.75).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.max / 3.75).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<h3>Food and Groceries</h3>
<p>Monthly groceries: SAR {city.food.groceriesMonthly.min.toLocaleString()}-{city.food.groceriesMonthly.max.toLocaleString()} (~€{Math.round(city.food.groceriesMonthly.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.food.groceriesMonthly.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()}). Budget meal: SAR {city.food.mealBudgetRestaurant.min}-{city.food.mealBudgetRestaurant.max}. Mid-range: SAR {city.food.mealMidRange.min}-{city.food.mealMidRange.max}. Tamimi Markets, Panda, Danube, and LuLu Hypermarket are the main grocery chains, with competitive pricing and wide product selection. Locally produced dairy, dates, and bread are significantly cheaper than imported alternatives. The 15% VAT applies to most food items, though some basic staples may be zero-rated. Shopping at discount outlets and buying in bulk can meaningfully reduce the monthly food budget. Fresh produce markets (souqs) offer seasonal fruits and vegetables at lower prices than supermarkets.</p>
<h3>Transport</h3>
<p>Petrol: SAR {city.transport.gasolinePerLiter.amount}/liter (~€{(city.transport.gasolinePerLiter.amount * 0.24).toFixed(2)}). Saudi Arabia is fundamentally car-oriented, with most expatriates owning or leasing vehicles. Fuel is among the cheapest in the world, making driving costs minimal. Car insurance runs SAR 1,500 to SAR 4,000 annually depending on vehicle type and coverage. The Saher camera system enforces speed limits and traffic regulations with automated fines managed through Absher. Uber and Careem operate in all major cities. The Riyadh Metro is expanding progressively, and the Haramain High-Speed Railway connects Makkah, Jeddah, and Madinah.</p>
<h3>Healthcare</h3>
<p>GP visit: SAR {city.healthcare.gpVisit.min}-{city.healthcare.gpVisit.max} (~€{Math.round(city.healthcare.gpVisit.min * 0.24)}-{Math.round(city.healthcare.gpVisit.max * 0.24)}). Specialist: SAR {city.healthcare.specialistVisit.min}-{city.healthcare.specialistVisit.max} (~€{Math.round(city.healthcare.specialistVisit.min * 0.24)}-{Math.round(city.healthcare.specialistVisit.max * 0.24)}). CCHI-approved health insurance is mandatory for all expatriates. Annual premiums range from SAR 2,500 for basic plans to SAR 10,000 for comprehensive coverage. Major hospital groups include Dr. Sulaiman Al Habib, Saudi German Hospitals, Dallah Health, and King Faisal Specialist Hospital. Pharmacies are widespread and most Western medications are readily available.</p>
<h3>Education</h3>
<p>International school fees: SAR {city.education.internationalSchool.min.toLocaleString()}-{city.education.internationalSchool.max.toLocaleString()} (~€{Math.round(city.education.internationalSchool.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.education.internationalSchool.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()})/year. Nursery: SAR {city.education.nursery.min.toLocaleString()}-{city.education.nursery.max.toLocaleString()} (~€{Math.round(city.education.nursery.min * 0.24).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.education.nursery.max * 0.24).toLocaleString()})/year. Indian-curriculum schools offer the most affordable option at SAR 10,000-22,000 annually. British and American curriculum schools range from SAR 25,000-60,000. Premium institutions in Riyadh reach SAR 80,000. Many employers include education allowances in compensation packages.</p>
<h3>Utilities</h3>
<p>SEC electricity and NWC water: SAR {city.utilities.monthly.min}-{city.utilities.monthly.max} (~€{Math.round(city.utilities.monthly.min * 0.24)}-{Math.round(city.utilities.monthly.max * 0.24)})/month. Internet: SAR {city.utilities.internet.min}-{city.utilities.internet.max} (~€{Math.round(city.utilities.internet.min * 0.24)}-{Math.round(city.utilities.internet.max * 0.24)}). Mobile: SAR {city.utilities.mobile.min}-{city.utilities.mobile.max} (~€{Math.round(city.utilities.mobile.min * 0.24)}-{Math.round(city.utilities.mobile.max * 0.24)}). Saudi Arabia's residential electricity rates benefit from government subsidies that keep costs low. Air conditioning drives most of the electricity bill, particularly during summer when temperatures exceed 45 degrees in Riyadh and the Eastern Province. The 15% VAT applies to all utility bills and telecom charges.</p>
</>
))}

<h2>The VAT Factor: How 15% Affects Your Budget</h2>
<p>Saudi Arabia's 15% VAT rate, the highest in the GCC, requires special attention when budgeting. On a monthly taxable spending of SAR 5,000, the VAT component is SAR 750. Over a year, that amounts to SAR 9,000 in VAT alone. Compared to the UAE's 5% rate, where the same spending incurs SAR 250 in VAT, Saudi Arabia's rate is three times higher. Compared to Qatar's zero VAT, the Saudi rate represents a pure cost addition of SAR 750 per month. However, the dramatically lower base prices in Saudi Arabia, particularly for housing and daily essentials, more than offset this VAT differential in absolute terms. A household spending SAR 5,000 on rent in Riyadh pays SAR 750 in VAT on other spending, totaling SAR 5,750. The same lifestyle in Dubai might cost AED 8,000 in rent alone, before any VAT on other spending. The net result is that Saudi Arabia remains the most affordable Gulf destination despite the higher VAT rate.</p>

<h2>Monthly Budget Examples</h2>
<p>A single professional in Riyadh earning SAR 15,000 might budget: rent SAR 3,500, groceries SAR 1,000, dining SAR 800, utilities SAR 300, transport SAR 500, mobile SAR 150, gym SAR 200, miscellaneous SAR 500. Total: approximately SAR 6,950. Monthly savings: SAR 8,050 (54% savings rate). Over two years, that professional accumulates SAR 193,200 in savings, entirely tax-free.</p>

<p>A family of four in Jeddah earning SAR 25,000 combined, with employer-provided compound housing: groceries SAR 1,600, school fees (monthly average) SAR 3,000, utilities SAR 400, transport SAR 600, dining and entertainment SAR 1,200, mobile and internet SAR 400, miscellaneous SAR 800. Total: approximately SAR 8,000. Monthly savings: SAR 17,000 (68% savings rate). Over a three-year assignment, the family saves SAR 612,000. These examples demonstrate why Saudi Arabia attracts professionals focused on building long-term financial security.</p>

<h2>How Saudi Arabia Compares</h2>
<p>Against Dubai, Saudi Arabia is 25% to 40% cheaper for comparable lifestyles, driven primarily by lower housing costs. Against Doha, Saudi Arabia has lower base prices but the 15% VAT partially erodes the advantage compared to Qatar's zero-VAT environment. For families, the combination of low housing costs, affordable schooling, and employer benefits packages that often include housing, education, and flights makes Saudi Arabia the clear leader for maximizing absolute savings. The trade-off is lifestyle: Dubai offers more entertainment, nightlife, and cosmopolitan diversity. Qatar offers zero VAT and a compact, modern city. Saudi Arabia offers the highest financial efficiency at the cost of a more conservative social environment, though one that is rapidly modernizing.</p>

<FAQAccordion faqs={faqs} />
<SourcesBlock sources={[{ name: "Saudi GASTAT", url: "https://www.stats.gov.sa/" }, { name: "Saudi Electricity Company", url: "https://www.se.com.sa/" }]} />
<RelatedLinks links={[{ label: "Saudi Salaries", href: "/saudi-arabia/salaries/" }, { label: "Riyadh Guide", href: "/saudi-arabia/riyadh/" }, { label: "Jeddah Guide", href: "/saudi-arabia/jeddah/" }, { label: "Dammam Guide", href: "/saudi-arabia/dammam/" }, { label: "UAE vs Saudi Arabia", href: "/compare/uae-vs-saudi-arabia/" }]} />
<script is:inline>
function _calcCostOfLiving(){var s=parseInt(document.getElementById('saSalary').value)||0,city=document.getElementById('saCity').value,h=document.getElementById('saHouse').value,rent={riyadh:3500,jeddah:3000,dammam:2500},other={riyadh:4500,jeddah:4000,dammam:3500},r=h==='yes'?0:rent[city],exp=r+other[city],sv=s-exp,rate=s>0?((sv/s)*100).toFixed(1):0;document.getElementById('saResult').innerHTML=sv>0?'<strong>Monthly savings: SAR '+sv.toLocaleString()+' (~EUR '+(sv*0.24|0).toLocaleString()+')</strong><br><span class=\'text-xs text-gray-500\'>Savings rate: '+rate+'% | Expenses: SAR '+exp.toLocaleString()+' (rent: SAR '+r.toLocaleString()+' + living: SAR '+other[city].toLocaleString()+'). Annual: SAR '+(sv*12).toLocaleString()+' saved tax-free.</span>':'<span class=\'text-red-600\'>Expenses SAR '+exp.toLocaleString()+' exceed salary.</span>';}
</script>
</GuideLayout>
